## 🎉 TDD Exercise Complete!

All 10 tests are now passing. The Conway's Game of Life implementation with an infinite sparse grid has been successfully completed through the Test-Driven Development process.

**Final Implementation Summary:**
- ✅ Empty grid handling
- ✅ Underpopulation rule (cells with <2 neighbors die)
- ✅ Survival rule (cells with 2-3 neighbors survive)
- ✅ Overpopulation rule (cells with >3 neighbors die)
- ✅ Reproduction rule (dead cells with exactly 3 neighbors become alive)
- ✅ Classic patterns support (blinker, block)
- ✅ Negative coordinate support (sparse grid in all directions)

**Code Quality:**
- Clean, well-named helper functions (`cellKey`, `keyToCoords`, `getNeighborKeys`, `countLiveNeighbors`, `shouldSurvive`, `shouldBeBorn`)
- No code duplication
- Self-documenting code with clear intent
- Type-safe implementation using TypeScript

The implementation correctly applies all four Game of Life rules and handles the infinite sparse grid using a Set-based approach for tracking living cells.
